# =============================================================================
# Region-node `.env` — operator tuning surface (NON-SECRET)
# =============================================================================
#
# docker compose AUTO-LOADS `.env` from this directory for `${VAR:-default}`
# interpolation in docker-compose-prod.yml. This is the single source of truth
# for the handful of knobs an operator tunes per node — set them ONCE here and
# every service resolves the same value, regardless of shell state or which
# subset of containers gets recreated.
#
#   cp .env.example .env      # then edit the values below
#
# `create-op-node bootstrap` GENERATES this file for you (a managed block
# delimited by `# >>> op-node managed >>>` … `# <<< op-node managed <<<`).
# You may add your own lines OUTSIDE that block; a re-bootstrap preserves them.
#
# SECRETS DO NOT GO HERE. Postgres/JWT/HMAC/Supabase credentials live in the
# macOS Keychain (hydrated into compose by `bin/op-compose`) and Supabase
# Vault — never in a plaintext `.env`. For the full list of every variable the
# stack reads (secrets included, for the `--env-file` reference path), see
# environments/.env.production.example. `.env` is git-ignored.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LLM model (Ollama) — shared by knowledge, region, and the workers
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The one model every LLM service runs. Ollama runs natively on macOS; the
# model MUST be pulled on the host (`ollama pull <model>`) — `create-op-node`
# bootstrap pulls it and `create-op-node verify` asserts it's present.
#
# Size to the node's unified memory (the LLM shares RAM with ~22 containers +
# Postgres), tiering on total footprint:
#   >= 64 GB  qwen3.6:35b-a3b   (35B MoE, ~3B active — fast on Apple Silicon)
#   32-64 GB  qwen3:14b
#   16-32 GB  qwen2.5:7b
#   <= 16 GB  qwen2.5:3b        (Mac Mini)
# The compose fallback is qwen2.5:3b (smallest, always-pullable) so a bare run
# works anywhere; set your real choice here.
LLM_MODEL=qwen2.5:7b

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NODE_ENV — production (default) vs development
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Leave UNSET (defaults to production) for a Tunnel-exposed node. In production
# the backend's CORS validator REQUIRES https:// origins, so a `--local-only`
# node that serves http://localhost origins MUST set development here or
# region + knowledge crash-loop on the CORS preflight. Setting it in `.env`
# (not the shell) makes it durable across recreates.
# NODE_ENV=development

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Embeddings — ONLY the knowledge service consumes these (RAG)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Default provider is `xenova` (in-process, bundled model) — no Ollama pull
# needed. Switch to `ollama` to use the host daemon; the URL default already
# points at the host (containers can't use localhost for the native daemon),
# and the model must be pulled like the LLM. Var names match the backend
# (packages/config-provider/src/configs/embeddings.config.ts).
# EMBEDDINGS_PROVIDER=ollama
# EMBEDDINGS_OLLAMA_URL=http://host.docker.internal:11434
# EMBEDDINGS_OLLAMA_MODEL=nomic-embed-text

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Other common overrides (uncomment to change)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Image tag to run. Defaults to the rolling `latest`; pin a sha-prefixed tag
# for a hot-fix or rollback (e.g. TAG=sha-abc1234).
# TAG=latest

# Comma-separated browser origins allowed by CORS. The default covers the
# local dev ports + your public Supabase URL; set this if you serve a public
# frontend on its own domain. Production origins must be https://.
# ALLOWED_ORIGINS=https://app.yournode.example

# WebAuthn (passkeys). Default `localhost` works for --local-only (browsers
# treat http://localhost as a secure context). Serving a real domain? Set BOTH
# to your values.
# WEBAUTHN_RP_ID=yournode.example
# WEBAUTHN_ORIGIN=https://app.yournode.example
